<section id="clot-heart-attack">
    <h2>How Blood Clots Cause Heart Attacks</h2>

    <p>A heart attack doesn't happen slowly - it happens in <strong>minutes</strong>. The immediate cause of most heart attacks is a blood clot (thrombus) that suddenly blocks a coronary artery, cutting off blood supply to part of the heart muscle.</p>

    <div class="warning-box">
        <h3>The Heart Attack Sequence</h3>
        <ol>
            <li><strong>Years of buildup:</strong> Atherosclerotic plaque develops in artery walls</li>
            <li><strong>Plaque becomes unstable:</strong> Inflammation weakens the plaque's fibrous cap</li>
            <li><strong>Rupture or erosion:</strong> The plaque cap tears or erodes</li>
            <li><strong>Clotting cascade triggers:</strong> Plaque contents exposed to blood trigger clotting</li>
            <li><strong>Thrombus forms:</strong> Blood clot rapidly grows on the plaque</li>
            <li><strong>Artery occludes:</strong> Clot blocks blood flow within minutes</li>
            <li><strong>Heart muscle dies:</strong> Without oxygen, heart cells begin dying immediately</li>
        </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="key-point">
        <h3>The Critical Insight</h3>
        <p>Heart attacks are not primarily about plaque size - they're about plaque <strong>stability</strong> and <strong>clotting tendency</strong>. A person with 30% blockage can have a fatal heart attack if that plaque ruptures and triggers a massive clot. Meanwhile, someone with 70% blockage may be stable if the plaque is calcified and their blood isn't prone to clotting.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>Why Some Plaques Rupture</h3>
    <p>Unstable ("vulnerable") plaques have these characteristics:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Thin fibrous cap:</strong> The protective covering is weak</li>
        <li><strong>Large lipid core:</strong> Soft, cholesterol-rich center</li>
        <li><strong>Inflammatory cells:</strong> Macrophages weaken the structure</li>
        <li><strong>Fewer smooth muscle cells:</strong> Less structural support</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Inflammation is the key driver of plaque instability. This is why insulin resistance and metabolic dysfunction - which cause chronic inflammation - dramatically increase heart attack risk.</p>
</section>

<section id="clot-formation">
    <h2>How Blood Clots Form (The Clotting Cascade)</h2>

    <p>Understanding how clots form reveals why metabolic health is so important for prevention.</p>

    <h3>The Three Components of Clot Formation (Virchow's Triad)</h3>
    <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1rem 0;">
        <tr style="background: #f8f8f8;">
            <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: left;">Factor</th>
            <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: left;">Description</th>
            <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: left;">Metabolic Connection</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;"><strong>Endothelial Injury</strong></td>
            <td style="padding: 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">Damage to blood vessel lining</td>
            <td style="padding: 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">High glucose and insulin damage endothelium</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;"><strong>Blood Stasis</strong></td>
            <td style="padding: 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">Sluggish or turbulent blood flow</td>
            <td style="padding: 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">Obesity, sedentary lifestyle, viscosity changes</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 1rem;"><strong>Hypercoagulability</strong></td>
            <td style="padding: 1rem;">Blood that clots too easily</td>
            <td style="padding: 1rem;">Insulin resistance increases clotting factors</td>
        </tr>
    </table>

    <h3>The Clotting Cascade Simplified</h3>
    <div class="timeline">
        <div class="timeline-item">
            <strong>1. Vessel Injury</strong>
            <p>Endothelium is damaged or plaque ruptures, exposing subendothelial tissue</p>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-item">
            <strong>2. Platelet Activation</strong>
            <p>Platelets adhere to damaged area and become activated, releasing chemicals</p>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-item">
            <strong>3. Platelet Aggregation</strong>
            <p>More platelets stick together, forming initial "plug"</p>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-item">
            <strong>4. Coagulation Cascade</strong>
            <p>Clotting factors activate in sequence, producing thrombin</p>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-item">
            <strong>5. Fibrin Formation</strong>
            <p>Thrombin converts fibrinogen to fibrin, creating mesh that stabilizes clot</p>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-item">
            <strong>6. Clot Stabilization</strong>
            <p>Cross-linked fibrin creates solid clot structure</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h3>Fibrinolysis: The Clot Breakdown System</h3>
    <p>Your body has a system to dissolve clots (fibrinolysis). In healthy individuals, there's a balance between clot formation and clot breakdown. In metabolic dysfunction, this balance is disrupted:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>PAI-1 (Plasminogen Activator Inhibitor-1):</strong> Elevated in insulin resistance, blocks clot breakdown</li>
        <li><strong>tPA (tissue Plasminogen Activator):</strong> May be impaired</li>
        <li><strong>Result:</strong> Clots form more easily and don't break down as effectively</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section id="arterial-venous">
    <h2>Arterial vs. Venous Blood Clots</h2>

    <p>Not all blood clots are the same. Understanding the difference is crucial:</p>

    <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1rem 0;">
        <tr style="background: #f8f8f8;">
            <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: left;">Feature</th>
            <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: left;">Arterial Clots</th>
            <th style="padding: 1rem; text-align: left;">Venous Clots</th>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;"><strong>Location</strong></td>
            <td style="padding: 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">Arteries (heart, brain, limbs)</td>
            <td style="padding: 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">Veins (legs, pelvis, lungs)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;"><strong>Composition</strong></td>
            <td style="padding: 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">Platelet-rich ("white clot")</td>
            <td style="padding: 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">Fibrin-rich ("red clot")</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;"><strong>Main cause</strong></td>
            <td style="padding: 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">Atherosclerosis, plaque rupture</td>
            <td style="padding: 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">Stasis, immobility, hypercoagulability</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;"><strong>Results in</strong></td>
            <td style="padding: 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">Heart attack, stroke, peripheral artery disease</td>
            <td style="padding: 1rem; border-bottom: 1px solid #eee;">DVT, pulmonary embolism</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td style="padding: 1rem;"><strong>Treatment</strong></td>
            <td style="padding: 1rem;">Antiplatelet drugs (aspirin, clopidogrel)</td>
            <td style="padding: 1rem;">Anticoagulants (heparin, warfarin, DOACs)</td>
        </tr>
    </table>

    <h3>Deep Vein Thrombosis (DVT)</h3>
    <p>Blood clots in the deep veins of the legs are called DVT. They're dangerous because they can:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Break loose and travel to the lungs (pulmonary embolism)</li>
        <li>Cause chronic leg swelling and pain (post-thrombotic syndrome)</li>
        <li>Indicate underlying clotting disorders or cancer</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Pulmonary Embolism (PE)</h3>
    <p>When a DVT breaks loose and travels to the lungs, it becomes a pulmonary embolism - a life-threatening emergency that blocks blood flow to the lungs.</p>
</section>

<section id="risk-factors">
    <h2>Risk Factors for Blood Clots</h2>

    <h3>Modifiable Risk Factors</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Obesity:</strong> Increases clotting factors and inflammation</li>
        <li><strong>Sedentary lifestyle:</strong> Blood stasis promotes clotting</li>
        <li><strong>Smoking:</strong> Damages endothelium, increases clotting</li>
        <li><strong>Poor diet:</strong> Refined carbs and seed oils promote inflammation</li>
        <li><strong>Dehydration:</strong> Thickens blood, promotes clotting</li>
        <li><strong>Metabolic syndrome:</strong> Pro-thrombotic state</li>
        <li><strong>Uncontrolled diabetes:</strong> Elevated glucose damages vessels</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Non-Modifiable Risk Factors</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Age:</strong> Clot risk increases with age</li>
        <li><strong>Genetics:</strong> Factor V Leiden, prothrombin mutations</li>
        <li><strong>Family history:</strong> First-degree relatives with clots</li>
        <li><strong>Previous clots:</strong> High recurrence risk</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Situational Risk Factors</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Surgery:</strong> Especially orthopedic procedures</li>
        <li><strong>Immobility:</strong> Long flights, bed rest, hospitalization</li>
        <li><strong>Pregnancy:</strong> Hypercoagulable state</li>
        <li><strong>Hormone therapy:</strong> Estrogen increases clotting</li>
        <li><strong>Cancer:</strong> Many cancers increase clotting risk</li>
        <li><strong>COVID-19:</strong> Associated with increased clotting</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section id="metabolic-connection">
    <h2>The Metabolic Connection: Why Insulin Resistance Causes Clots</h2>

    <p>Insulin resistance doesn't just cause diabetes - it creates a <strong>pro-thrombotic state</strong> that dramatically increases clot risk.</p>

    <div class="warning-box">
        <h3>How Insulin Resistance Promotes Clotting</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Elevated PAI-1:</strong> Insulin resistance raises PAI-1 levels 2-4x, blocking natural clot breakdown</li>
            <li><strong>Increased fibrinogen:</strong> Higher levels mean more raw material for clots</li>
            <li><strong>Platelet hyperactivity:</strong> Platelets become more "sticky" and aggregate more easily</li>
            <li><strong>Endothelial dysfunction:</strong> Damaged vessel lining triggers clotting</li>
            <li><strong>Chronic inflammation:</strong> Inflammatory cytokines activate clotting cascade</li>
            <li><strong>Elevated Factor VII:</strong> Increased clotting factor production</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>The Visceral Fat Connection</h3>
    <p>Belly fat (visceral adipose tissue) isn't just storage - it's an active endocrine organ that pumps out:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>PAI-1:</strong> Directly secreted by visceral fat</li>
        <li><strong>IL-6:</strong> Stimulates liver to produce clotting factors</li>
        <li><strong>TNF-α:</strong> Promotes inflammation and clotting</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="key-point">
        <h3>The Core Message</h3>
        <p>Addressing insulin resistance isn't just about preventing diabetes - it's about preventing the clots that cause heart attacks. Every metabolic health intervention (fasting, low-carb eating, exercise) reduces your clotting risk.</p>
    </div>
</section>

<section id="inflammation">
    <h2>Inflammation: The Link Between Metabolism and Clotting</h2>

    <p>Inflammation is the bridge connecting metabolic dysfunction to blood clots. Chronic low-grade inflammation:</p>

    <ul>
        <li>Damages the endothelium, creating sites for clot formation</li>
        <li>Makes atherosclerotic plaques unstable and prone to rupture</li>
        <li>Activates the clotting cascade</li>
        <li>Inhibits natural clot breakdown</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Inflammatory Markers That Predict Clot Risk</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>hs-CRP:</strong> High-sensitivity C-reactive protein - elevated in inflammation</li>
        <li><strong>Fibrinogen:</strong> Both a clotting factor and inflammatory marker</li>
        <li><strong>IL-6:</strong> Pro-inflammatory cytokine</li>
        <li><strong>Homocysteine:</strong> Associated with clotting and vascular damage</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>What Causes Chronic Inflammation?</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Insulin resistance and hyperglycemia</li>
        <li>Visceral obesity</li>
        <li>Seed oils (omega-6 excess)</li>
        <li>Processed foods and refined carbohydrates</li>
        <li>Chronic stress</li>
        <li>Poor sleep</li>
        <li>Gut dysbiosis and leaky gut</li>
    </ul>
</section>

