<section id="natural-blood-thinners">
    <h2>Natural Approaches to Blood Clot Prevention</h2>

    <div class="warning-box">
        <h3>Important Warning</h3>
        <p>Never stop prescribed blood thinners without medical supervision. Natural approaches are for prevention in healthy individuals, not replacement of medical treatment. Always discuss supplements with your doctor, especially if on any medications.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>Evidence-Based Natural Approaches</h3>

    <h4>1. Nattokinase</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Enzyme from fermented soybeans (natto)</li>
        <li>Has fibrinolytic activity (breaks down fibrin)</li>
        <li>May reduce blood viscosity</li>
        <li>Typical dose: 2,000-4,000 FU daily</li>
        <li><strong>Caution:</strong> Avoid with blood thinners</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>2. Omega-3 Fatty Acids</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Reduce platelet aggregation</li>
        <li>Anti-inflammatory effects</li>
        <li>Support healthy endothelium</li>
        <li>Sources: fatty fish, fish oil, algae oil</li>
        <li>Typical dose: 2-4 grams EPA/DHA daily</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>3. Vitamin E (Mixed Tocopherols)</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Mild antiplatelet effects</li>
        <li>Antioxidant protection for vessels</li>
        <li>Use mixed tocopherols, not just alpha</li>
        <li>Typical dose: 200-400 IU daily</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>4. Garlic</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Reduces platelet aggregation</li>
        <li>May lower blood pressure</li>
        <li>Anti-inflammatory properties</li>
        <li>Aged garlic extract is best studied</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>5. Anti-Inflammatory Foods</h4>
    <ul>
        <li>Fatty fish (salmon, sardines, mackerel)</li>
        <li>Olive oil (extra virgin)</li>
        <li>Leafy greens</li>
        <li>Berries</li>
        <li>Turmeric/curcumin</li>
        <li>Ginger</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Foods That May Increase Clotting Risk</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Seed oils (inflammatory omega-6)</li>
        <li>Refined carbohydrates (spike insulin)</li>
        <li>Trans fats</li>
        <li>Excessive sugar</li>
        <li>Processed meats</li>
    </ul>
</section>

